A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage was performed when the respondent was suffering from a mental disorder (Section 12(1)(a) HMA);
2. if the respondent was suffering from a mental illness or disorder at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA);
3. if the respondent was impotent at the time of the marriage and continues to be so (Section 12(1)(a) HMA, however, this is more specifically covered under Section 12(1)(a) for a spouse's impotency);
4. if the respondent had an unsound mind or was suffering from a mental disorder at the time of the registration of marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA);
5. if consent was obtained by force, coercion, or fraud (Section 12(1)(c) HMA);
6. if the pregnancy of the respondent at the time of marriage was as a result of someone other than the petitioner (Section 12(1)(d) HMA);
7. if the respondent was suffering from venereal disease in a communicable form at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(e) HMA);
8. if the respondent had an incurable form of leprosy at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(f) HMA);
9. if the respondent had voluntarily renounced the world by becoming a sanyasi, hermit, or a recluse (Section 12(1)(g) HMA).

